When the celebrated Tansen was ordered to sing a night raga in the afternoon by the Emperor, it is said darkness descended on the palace due to his powerful exposition. Nuances of time for rendering a raga is a time-honoured practice both in the Hindustani and Carnatic classical streams, although only a few follow such rules.This year’s theme of Bharatiya Samagana Sabha’s 7{+t}{+h}annual music fest (from January 27 to 31, Chowdiah Memorial Hall) is termed ‘Samaya Raga Sangeetothsava’, laying emphasis on the use and rendering of ragas according to time.R.R. Ravishankar of Bharatiya Samagana Sabha says, “Our Samaya Raga will be rendered on January 30 (9 a.m. to 6 p.m.) by nearly 30 youngsters covering a host of ragas from morning to evening in seven concerts.”The concluding day (January 31) will host Tyagaraja Aradhane celebrations with jugalbandi by Shashank Subramanyam (flute) and Abhishek Raghuram (vocal); and Purandara Aradhane with Sangeetha Katti on Hindustani vocal, which would be telecast live by DD Bharati (National) and DD Chandana from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m.The Samagana Mathanga National Award would be bestowed on Pt. Hariprasad Chaurasia at 5 p.m.